      <p class="lead">
        Every major field that studies human judgment — psychology, behavioral economics, medicine, law, intelligence analysis — has reached the same conclusion: knowing about cognitive biases does not reliably prevent them. Thousands of experiments have confirmed that experts who understand confirmation bias still seek confirming evidence, that trained judges still anchor on arbitrary numbers, that experienced investors still fall for the sunk cost fallacy. The knowledge is real; the protection it offers is largely illusory. The implication is uncomfortable but important: if you want to think more clearly, you cannot simply try harder to be objective. You have to change the structure of how you make decisions — not your intentions, but your process.
      </p>

      <section id="why-awareness-fails">
        <h2>Why Knowing About Biases Doesn't Stop Them</h2>
        <p>
          Daniel Kahneman, whose Nobel Prize-winning work on cognitive biases is the most widely read in the field, has been explicit on this point: "I've been studying biases for decades and I don't think I've become less biased." The reason is structural. Cognitive biases are primarily products of System 1 — the fast, automatic, unconscious processing that generates intuitions, first impressions, and emotional reactions before conscious reasoning begins. System 2 — the slow, deliberate, effortful reasoning that evaluates those intuitions — operates downstream. By the time you consciously reflect on a judgment, System 1 has already shaped it.
        </p>
        <p>
          When you become aware of a bias, that awareness lives in System 2. But the bias originates in System 1. The awareness arrives after the bias has already influenced the intuition it is supposed to prevent. This is why telling yourself "I should watch out for confirmation bias" while researching a decision rarely helps: the confirmation-biased information gathering happens before you consciously notice it, and what you notice — the evidence already selectively gathered — feels like a complete and representative picture.
        </p>

        <ContentBox type="warning" title="The Bias Blind Spot">
          <p>Research by Emily Pronin at Princeton showed that people rate themselves as significantly less biased than the average person — even after being educated about cognitive biases. More troublingly, the more people learn about cognitive biases, the more confidently they identify them in others while remaining blind to them in themselves. This "bias blind spot" means that education about biases can paradoxically increase the confidence with which people hold biased judgments, because they feel they are sophisticated enough to recognize bias when it affects them. They are not.</p>
        </ContentBox>

        <p>
          The practical implication of this research is that the path to better decisions does not run primarily through greater self-awareness or stronger intentions to be objective. It runs through process design — building decision-making structures that catch bias at the procedural level, before it determines the final output. Debiasing works when it changes what information is gathered, in what order, by whom, and how it is evaluated. It rarely works when it simply asks people to try to be more rational.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="most-costly-biases">
        <h2>The Most Costly Biases in Decisions</h2>
        <p>
          Not all biases deserve equal debiasing effort. Research on decision failures across business, medicine, law, intelligence analysis, and personal finance consistently identifies the same handful of biases as most consequential. Understanding which biases cause the most damage in practice — rather than which biases are most interesting in theory — is the starting point for a practical debiasing strategy.
        </p>

        <ContentGrid columns={2}>
          <ContentBox type="warning" title="Confirmation Bias">
            <p>Seeking, interpreting, and remembering information in ways that confirm existing beliefs. The most pervasive of all biases — affects information gathering, evaluation, and recall simultaneously. Particularly damaging for strategic decisions where the decision-maker has already formed a directional preference.</p>
          </ContentBox>
          <ContentBox type="warning" title="Overconfidence Bias">
            <p>Systematically overestimating the accuracy of one's own judgments, the reliability of one's knowledge, and the probability of favorable outcomes. Research finds that people claiming 90% confidence in answers are typically correct only 70% of the time. Produces systematic underestimation of risk and project timelines.</p>
          </ContentBox>
          <ContentBox type="warning" title="Anchoring Effect">
            <p>Over-relying on the first piece of information encountered (the anchor) when making subsequent judgments. Even arbitrary anchors — random numbers, clearly irrelevant information — produce significant distortions in subsequent estimates. Particularly consequential in negotiations, project planning, and financial forecasting.</p>
          </ContentBox>
          <ContentBox type="warning" title="Sunk Cost Fallacy">
            <p>Continuing to invest in failing courses of action because of past investment (time, money, effort) that cannot be recovered. The rational response to sunk costs is to ignore them entirely — only future costs and benefits are relevant to current decisions. But people systematically fail to do this, prolonging bad investments and failed strategies.</p>
          </ContentBox>
          <ContentBox type="warning" title="Availability Heuristic">
            <p>Judging the probability of events by how easily examples come to mind. Dramatic, recent, or emotionally vivid events are overweighted; mundane but statistically more common events are underweighted. Produces systematic distortions in risk assessment — people fear plane crashes more than car accidents despite the opposite risk profile.</p>
          </ContentBox>
          <ContentBox type="warning" title="Planning Fallacy">
            <p>Systematically underestimating the time, cost, and risk required to complete future projects while overestimating the benefits — even when aware of past underestimates. Identified by Kahneman and Tversky, it affects virtually all project planning at the individual and organizational level. Most projects take 2-3x their original estimate.</p>
          </ContentBox>
        </ContentGrid>
      </section>

